### Description

I really like, that `FormValueControl` components have access to the config of the standard validators like `min` and `max` value, a feature we missed with Reactive Forms. üëç 

Continuing this line of thought, I would also like to be able to provide configurations of my own validators.

An example is shown in [stackblitz.com/edit/signal-forms-esh4c2uh](https://stackblitz.com/edit/signal-forms-esh4c2uh?file=src%2Fform%2Fselect.ts)  
A custom validator `options` validates a form field's value is part of a defined list  
and a custom `FormValueControl` component needs the allowed options to display them in a `select` element.  

I tried to replicate the logic with the `MetadataKey` from the built-in validators, but was not able to access this from the `FormValueControl` component.

Maybe someone can show me how this can be done, if there is already an option.

### Proposed solution

Instead of assigning the metadata as individual inputs to the `FormValueControl` component, I think it would be more streamlined to get access to some kind of metadata registry ‚Äî via input or dependency injection. This registry could include built-in configs like `min`, `minLength`, ‚Ä¶ as well as metadata from custom validators.

**Inject Approach**
```ts
import { FormValueControl, MetadataRegistry, MIN } from '@angular/forms/signals';
import { OPTIONS } from './custom-options-validator.ts';

@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class Select implements FormValueControl<string> {
  readonly value = model<string>('');

  readonly metadata = inject(MetadataRegistry);
  // built-in metadata from min validator
  readonly min = computed(() => this.metadata.get(MIN)());
  // custom metadata from custom options validator
  readonly options = computed(() => this.metadata.get(OPTIONS)());
}
```

**Input Approach**
```ts
import { FormValueControl, MetadataRegistry, MIN } from '@angular/forms/signals';
import { OPTIONS } from './custom-options-validator.ts';

@Component({ /* ... */ })
export class Select implements FormValueControl<string> {
  readonly value = model<string>('');

  readonly metadata = input.required<MetadataRegistry>();
  // built-in metadata from min validator
  readonly min = computed(() => this.metadata().get(MIN)());
  // custom metadata from custom options validator
  readonly options = computed(() => this.metadata().get(OPTIONS)());
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Alternatively, the validator config can be passed as dedicated inputs (like in the linked stackblitz). But this requires the state to be kept in sync between the input and the validator. This is possible but can get out of hand for bigger forms with a lot of fields with different validator configs.  
This would make the custom validator some kind of second class citizens in contrast to the built-in validators.

